tinuing relationship between Jewish and Islamic thought in the late fourteenth and early fifteenth centuries. The text's most lasting effect may have been exerted via its passage to Renaissance Italy, where it influenced scholars at the University of Padua in the early sixteenth century. With its crucial role in the development of European astronomy, as well as the physical sciences under Islam and in Jewish culture, The Light of the World is an important episode in Islamic intellectual history, Jewish civilization, and the history of astronomy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAstrologyxHistoryvSources. 0aAstrologyxSourcesxHistory. 0aAstrology, SpanishxHistoryvSources. 0aAstrology, SpanishxSourcesxHistory. 0aAstronomyxSourcesxHistoryxSpainxAndalusiaxSpainxAndalusia. 0aAstronomyzSpainzAndalusiaxHistoryvSources. 0aAstronomy, MedievalxSourcesxHistoryxSpainxAndalusia. 0aAstronomy, MedievalzSpainzAndalusiaxHistoryvSources. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016z978311066754708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520963030423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520963030.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066754-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles